1. Documentation

1.1 Highlight

  • Discover the structure of a online documentation
  • Apply webscapying toolkit (R package rvest, similar to bs4 in python) with HTML tag and CSS selector to scrap information from online pages.
  • Use functional programming toolkit (R package purrr) to duplicate the same operation on a list of value
  • Use parallel computing (R package furrr) to speed up the functional programming method about 5 time.

1.2 Method

I take “https://www.instagram.com/developer/” as the base url to navigate all pages under this base url as well as their direct-linked pages not under the base. The scraping is done by parallel processing on multi-cores and functional programming method. The information obtained from the scraping is the hyperlink with html tag a, title of the page with html tag title, the first header with html tag h1. The obtained dataset is store in two data frame. The data frame elist contains edge information: variable From is the page url and variable To is the hyperlinks in the page. The data frame Vattrs contain vertex information: variable names is the page url; the variable title is the title of the url; the variable h1 is the first header of the url.

1.3 A Little more Story Why Doing this.

My goal of this web scraping assignment is to challenge myself on nagivating a large website by using only coding and scraping useful information. I was really interested in API scraping, so I try to read the tweeter API documentation and that is so difficult to understand because the page layout and hyperlink connection are so confusing. Besides, the description is not helpfull at all. So I compared the tweeter API documentation with Facebook, Microsoft, Linkedin, and Instagram. I found the one by Instagram is really easy to understand. So I perform a network data analysis on the Hyperlink connection across the Instagram API Documentation.

2.2 scrapEdge

# the base url
url <- "https://www.instagram.com/developer/"

ptm <- proc.time() # initial timming
repeat {
  # dynamic plot during scraping
  # flush.console() 
  if (exists("monitor") == FALSE){ # for the first url
    # find all href for this url
    elist <- scrapEdge(url) %>% na.omit() 
    # find nav href for a html url
    elist_nav_raw <- scrapEdge_nav(url) %>% select(To) %>% as.vector()
    elist_nav_raw <- elist_nav_raw[!elist_nav_raw == url]
    # construct monitor(time,links)
    monitor <- data.frame(time = as.vector((proc.time() - ptm)[3]), 
                          links = nrow(elist)) 
  }
  # rbind elist
  elist <- rbind(elist, furrr::future_map_dfr(elist$To[str_detect(elist$To, url)] %>% unique() %>% na.omit(), 
                                              scrapEdge)) %>% 
    distinct() 
  # rbind monitor
  monitor <- rbind(monitor, 
                   data.frame(time = as.vector((proc.time() - ptm)[3]), 
                              links = nrow(elist))) 
  # dynamic plot
  # plot(monitor$time,monitor$links,type='l', xlim=c(0,max(monitor$time)),
  #      xlab="Time in seconds", ylab="Number of href Links")
  # title(paste0("Scraping Hyperlink Connection: ", url))
  
  # break criterion
  if (length(unique(tail(monitor$links,2))) == 1 & nrow(monitor)>=2){
    break
  }
  if (max(monitor$links) > 2000){
    break
  }
}

2.4 Descriptive Analysis

2.4.1 Vertex Degree Distribution

There is more out connection compare to the in connection. It shows the degree documentation using external resouce relative to the internal resource. Noticeably, there are more url has number of hyperlink less than ten than that more than 20, which show a hierarchy sturcture.

# VertexD egree

2.4.2 Vertex Centrality

library(sna)
  • degree centrality shows there distinguish three type of url in this website, which are navigational page, detail guide page, and external page.
  • Closeness centrality shows some vertice are more ‘central’ becaise they are close to many other vertices
  • Betweenness centrality shows only a few vertice are located between (on the path) other pairs of vertices
  • eigenvector centrality show haft of the vertice are more central the neighbors of a vertex are, therefore, the more central that vertex itself is.
# VertexCentrality
A <- get.adjacency(g, sparse=FALSE) 
library(network)
g.netmat <- network::as.network.matrix(A) 
# The head teacher and instructor are indicated with blue and yellow, respectively
par(mfrow=c(2,2), mar=c(1, 1, 1, 1))
sna::gplot.target(g.netmat, degree(g.netmat), 
                  main="Degree", circ.col="skyblue",
                  usearrows = FALSE, circ.lab = FALSE,
                  vertex.col=c("blue", rep("red", 32), "yellow"), 
                  edge.col="darkgray")
sna::gplot.target(g.netmat, closeness(g.netmat), 
                  main="Closeness", circ.col="skyblue",
                  usearrows = FALSE, circ.lab = FALSE,
                  vertex.col=c("blue", rep("red", 32), "yellow"), 
                  edge.col="darkgray")
sna::gplot.target(g.netmat, betweenness(g.netmat), 
                  main="Betweenness", circ.col="skyblue",
                  usearrows = FALSE, circ.lab = FALSE,
                  vertex.col=c("blue", rep("red", 32), "yellow"), 
                  edge.col="darkgray")
sna::gplot.target(g.netmat, evcent(g.netmat), 
                  main="Eigenvector", circ.col="skyblue",
                  usearrows = FALSE, circ.lab = FALSE,
                  vertex.col=c("blue", rep("red", 32), "yellow"), 
                  edge.col="darkgray")

  • hub.score score the importance of so-called hub vertices by how many authority vertices they point to, according to the eigenvector centrality of the matrix M_hub = A A^T
  • authority.score scores the importance of so-called authority vertices by how many hubs point to them, according to the eigenvector centrality of the matrix M_auth = A^T A.
par(mfrow=c(1,2), mar=c(1, 1, 1, 1))
l <- layout.kamada.kawai(g)
plot(g, layout=l, main="Hubs", vertex.label="",
     vertex.size=10 * sqrt(hub.score(g)$vector)) 
plot(g, layout=l,
     main="Authorities", vertex.label="", 
     vertex.size=10 * sqrt(authority.score(g)$vector))

  # options
  visOptions(highlightNearest = list(enabled = T, hover = T), 
             nodesIdSelection = T)

A. Appendix: ud_funcion.R

cleanText <- function(x){
  x <- gsub("[[:blank:]]", "", x) 
  x <-  gsub("\n", "", x) # clean up the links names
  return(x)
}

# find all href for a html url
scrapEdge <- function(url) {
  tryCatch({
    html <- read_html(url) # parse to html
    links <- html %>% html_nodes('a') %>% html_attr(name="href"); links # obtain the href
    linkName <- html %>% html_nodes('a') %>% html_text() %>% cleanText() # obtain the href text
    elist <- tibble(From = rep(url,length(links)), 
                    To = url_absolute(links,url) %>% as.character(),
                    linkName = linkName ) %>% 
      na.omit()# construct elist(From,To)
    return(elist)
  }, error = function(e) {cat("ERROR :",conditionMessage(e), " ", url, "\n")})
}

# find nav href for a html url
scrapEdge_nav <- function(url) {
  tryCatch({
    html <- read_html(url) # parse to html
    links <- html %>% html_nodes('nav a') %>% html_attr(name="href"); links # obtain the href
    linkName <- html %>% html_nodes('nav a') %>% html_text() %>% cleanText() # obtain the href text
    elist <- data.frame(From = rep(url,length(links)), 
                        To = url_absolute(links,url) %>% as.character(),
                        linkName = linkName ,
                        stringsAsFactors = FALSE) %>% 
      na.omit()# construct elist(From,To)
    return(elist)
  }, error = function(e) {cat("ERROR :",conditionMessage(e), " ", url, "\n")})
}

# scrap attrs for a url
scrapAttrs <- function(url){
  html <- try(read_html(url), silent = TRUE) 
  if (class(html) != "try-error"){
    title <-html %>% html_node("title") %>% html_text() %>% cleanText()
    h1 <- html %>% html_node("h1") %>% html_text() %>% cleanText()
  } else {
    title <- html[1]
    h1 <- html[1]
  }
  vattr <- tibble(Name = url, Title = title, h1 = h1)
  return(vattr)
}

# scrap attrs for a list of url
scrapVertex <- function(elist){
  # construct a vector of url
  links <- append(as.vector(elist$From), as.vector(elist$To)) %>% 
    unique() %>% 
    na.omit()
  
  # scrapy attr for each html page
  vattrs <- furrr::future_map_dfr(links, function(x) try(scrapAttrs(x),silent = TRUE))
  return(vattrs)
}
